Australians shocked by the Boston marathon bombing: PM
2013-04-16 03:29:46 GMT
CANBERRA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Australians have been shocked by the tragic scenes in the United States, where three people were killed and more than 100 injured as two explosions tore through Boston Marathon runners and spectators, Prime Minister Julia Gillard said on Tuesday.Speaking at a press conference in Canberra, she condemned this "brutal and senseless attack." "Australia unreservedly condemns the brutal and senseless attack on what is a great event known around the world, and one people participate in to have fun as their families and friends watch on," Gillard said.In a statement from her earlier today, Gillard said Australians ' condolences go to the families of those killed and our thoughts are with those who have been injured.According to her, there is no evidence showing any Australian has been injured in the marathon bombing. "At this stage we are not aware of any Australian victims, so we do not have any evidence of course at the moment that any Australians have been hurt in this incident," she said.And Opposition Leader Tony Abbott said the thoughts of all Australians were with the people of Boston as they reeled from the bombing of the iconic running event."The coalition joins with the government in expressing our shock and sorrow at this morning's terrible events," he said in a statement today. 
